Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
setPtnPinStatus(25.10)                                  setPtnPinStatus(25.10)

Name
       setPtnPinStatus  -  Sets  the  pin  status  for a pin of a partition as
       fixed, placed, cover, or unplaced

Syntax
        setPtnPinStatus

       [-help]

       [-selectedPinStatus {fixed | placed | cover}]

       [-pin {<pinName >| <pinNameList>}]

       [-status {fixed | placed | unplaced | cover}]

       {[-pin {<pinName >| <pinNameList>} -status{fixed | placed | unplaced  |
       cover} [-cell <partitionName>]] }

       Sets  the  pin status for a pin of a partition as fixed, placed, cover,
       or unplaced. The setPtnPinStatus command operates, like a lot of  other
       pin  commands, on the top cell in addition to on partitions. If the top
       cell name is specified, or if setPtnPinStatus receives  a  "*"  as  its
       first argument, the IO pin status is modified. You can use this command
       any time after assigning pins.

       Note:

              * Use this command to unassign blackbox pins before the blackbox
                is  committed. To unassign blackbox pins after the blackbox is
                committed, use the flattenPartition command instead.

              * If this command is run on a blackbox that has one or more pins
                with a single LEF port but with multiple shapes within the LEF
                port, the command will remove these multiple shapes and create
                a single shape. If this command is run on a blackbox that  has
                one  or  more pins with multiple LEF ports, the first LEF port
                will be processed as per the command  and  the  remaining  LEF
                ports will remain unchanged.

Parameters
       -cell <partitionName>
              Specifies  the name of the partition. You can use wildcards (*?)
              with this parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes type and  default  in-
              formation for each setPtnPinStatus parameter. For a detailed de-
              scription  of the command and all of its parameters, use the man
              command:

              man setPtnPinStatus.

       -pin <pinName> | <pinNameList>
              Specifies the name of the pin(s) of the partition. You  can  use
              wildcards (*?) with this parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -selectedPinStatus {fixed | placed | cover}
              Selects  pins  with  only specified status. This options enables
              the setPtnPinStatus command to change  the  status  of  selected
              pins based on their present status and not just the names.

              * fixed: Selects pins with fixed status.

              * placed: Selects pins with placed status.

              * cover: Selects pins with cover status.

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -status {fixed | placed | unplaced | cover}
              Specifies the status of the pin.

              * Fixed: Fixed pin status specifies the pin's location, orienta-
                tion,  and  that  it's  location  cannot be moved by automatic
                tools, but can be moved by interactive commands.

                Note: Fixed pins can be moved by automatic pin assignment com-
                mands by using the -moveFixed parameter.

              * Placed: Placed pin status specifies the pin's location, orien-
                tation, and that it's location is fixed, but can be moved dur-
                ing automatic layout.

              * Unplaced: Unplaced pin status specifies that the pin does  not
                have a location.

              * cover: Cover pin status specifies the pin's location, orienta-
                tion,  and  that  it is a part of the cover macro. A cover pin
                cannot be moved by automatic tools or by interactive commands.

              Data_type: enum, optional

Example
       The following command marks all partition pins to fixed:

       setPtnPinStatus -cell * -pin * -status fixed

